Some shrines, such as '''Hibara Shrine, Kasayama Kōjinja, and Obu Tenjinja''', are '''located deep in the mountains'''. Additionally, the name '''Jinraku (秦楽)''', associated with Kasanui Shrine, is also found '''in the plains below the front part of the {{ill|Tsukiyama Kofun|ja|築山古墳|12=draft|12=draft}} in {{ill|Yamatotakada, Nara|ja|大和高田市|12=draft|12=draft}}''', where it was historically written as '''"神楽" (Jinraku/Kagura)'''. This could suggest some connection{{citation needed|date=June 2024}}.
From '''Tashinja''', looking in the direction of '''Yatsugikamino Mikoto Shrine (矢継ぎ神命神社)''' (dedicated to '''Tenmyō Toyotama no Mikoto'''), one faces the '''Jinraku and Tsukiyama Kofun direction'''. However, due to '''Yatsugi no Mori (矢継ぎの森)''', a sacred grove preserved by locals, '''the view is blocked'''.
It is also speculated that '''in ancient times, the view from Tashinja to Hime-Ōji Shrine may have included the {{ill|Hashihaka Kofun|ja|箸墓|12=draft|12=draft}}'''. Originally, '''Hime-Ōji Shrine was located to the north (upper seat) of Tashinja''', but was possibly '''relocated southward (lower seat)'''{{citation needed|date=June 2024}}.
If '''Tashinja is indeed the site of Kasanui-mura''', then these kofun formations might correspond to '''the origins of the {{ill|Daijōsai|ja|大嘗祭|12=draft|12=draft}}'s {{ill|Yuki-den|ja|悠紀殿|12=draft|12=draft}}''' (which has '''cut-inward 千木 [Chigi] like {{ill|Kōtai Jingu|ja|皇大神宮|1=Kōtai Jingū|2=ja|3=皇大神宮|4=zh|5=皇大神宮|12=draft|12=draft}}''') and '''Shuki-den (主基殿)''' (which has '''cut-outward Chigi like {{ill|Toyoukedai Jingu|ja|豊受大神宮|1=Toyouke Daijingu|2=ja|3=豊受大神宮|4=zh|5=豐受大神宮|12=draft|12=draft}}'''){{r|Heisei Daijōsai/p182}}{{citation needed|date=June 2024}}.
== Kasanui Island in Osaka == At '''{{ill|Fukae Inari Shrine|ja|深江稲荷神社|12=draft|12=draft}}''' ({{ill|Higashinari-ku, Osaka|ja|大阪市 東成区|12=draft|12=draft}} '''Fukaeminami'''), there is a tradition that '''Fukae was once the residence of the {{ill|Kasanui clan|ja|笠縫氏|12=draft|12=draft}}''', who migrated from '''Kasanui-mura in Yamato'''.
The '''Man'yōshū poet, {{ill|Takechi no Kurohito|ja|高市黒人|12=draft|12=draft}}''', wrote: > *"Shihatsu-yama uchi-koe mireba Kasanui no shima kogi-kakuru tana nashi kobune"* > *("Crossing over Mount Shihatsu, I see Kasanui Island, where small boats without roofs disappear.")*
In ancient times, '''Kasanui Island''' was believed to have been an island in an inlet '''stretching from present-day Fukae to {{ill|Higashiōsaka, Osaka|ja|東大阪市|12=draft|12=draft}} Ashiya'''. The '''Kasanui clan likely lived on the island''' to secure '''materials for making straw hats (笠, kasa)'''. This suggests that '''the original Kasanui-mura in Yamato might also have been a low-lying wetland or an island-like terrain'''{{who|date=June 2024}}.
Even today, '''the straw hats used in the Daijōsai are made in Fukae and presented to the Imperial Household'''. Additionally, '''Fukae has strong historical ties to the casting of the Imperial Divine Mirror (御神鏡)''', suggesting a connection with '''{{ill|Kagamitsukuri Shrine|ja|鏡作神社|12=draft|12=draft}}''' in '''Shiki District, Tawaramoto Town, Yao'''{{citation needed|date=June 2024}}.
