[[sn:Kasanuimura]] [[en:Kasanuimura]] [[ja:笠縫邑]]

'''{{ill|Kasanui-mura|ja|笠縫邑|qq=draft|qq=draft}}''' (かさぬいむら, かさぬいのむら) is the place where '''{{ill|Amaterasu|ja|天照大神|1=Amaterasu|lt=Amaterasu Ōmikami|qq=draft|qq=draft}}''' was '''transferred from the imperial palace in the 6th year of Emperor {{ill|Suijin|ja|崇神天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft}}'s reign''' and entrusted to '''{{ill|Toyosukiiri-hime no Mikoto|ja|豊鍬入姫命|1=Toyosukiiri-hime|qq=draft|qq=draft}}''' for enshrinement. At the same time, '''{{ill|Yamato Ōkunidama no Kami|ja|倭大国魂神|qq=draft|qq=draft}}''', who was also removed from the imperial palace, was entrusted to '''{{ill|Nunakiirihime no Mikoto|ja|渟名城入媛命|qq=draft|qq=draft}}''' and later enshrined at '''{{ill|Ōyamato Shrine|ja|大和神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}}'''{{citation needed|date=June 2024}}.
== Overview == There is a theory that '''Kasanui-mura is related to the origins of the {{ill|Daijōsai|ja|大嘗祭|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Toyoakari no Sechie|ja|豊明節会|qq=draft|qq=draft}}'''{{citation needed|date=June 2024}}. According to the '''25th year of Emperor {{ill|Suinin|ja|垂仁天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft}}'s reign''', '''Princess {{ill|Yamatohime-no-Mikoto|ja|倭姫命|1=Yamatohime-no-mikoto|qq=draft|qq=draft}}''' enshrined '''Amaterasu''' at '''{{ill|Ishiki no Ihokashi no Moto|ja|磯城の厳橿の本|qq=draft|qq=draft}}'''. The '''Ihokashi tree''' was considered a '''sacred tree for divine spirits''', and during Emperor Suijin's reign, the '''divine pillar of {{ill|Isokashiro Shrine|ja|磯堅城の神籬|qq=draft|qq=draft}}''' was erected ('''Suijin Chronicles, 6th year'''){{who|date=June 2024}}. In '''{{ill|Kogo Shūi|ja|古語拾遺|qq=draft|qq=draft}}''', it is referred to as '''"Ishiki no Himorogi"''', suggesting that '''"Ishiki no Ihokashi no Moto" and "Isokashiro no Himorogi"''' might be the same place{{who|date=June 2024}}.
=== Possible Locations=== There are various theories about the '''location of Kasanui-mura''', including: * '''{{ill|Hibara Shrine (Nara)|ja|檜原神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}}''' ({{ill|Sakurai, Nara|ja|桜井市|qq=draft|qq=draft}} '''Miwa''') * '''{{ill|Tashinja|ja|多神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}}''' ({{ill|Shiki District, Nara|ja|磯城郡|qq=draft|qq=draft}} '''Tawaramoto Town, Ta''') * '''{{ill|Kasanui Shrine|ja|笠縫神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}}''' (Shiki District, Tawaramoto Town, '''Hazushō''', located in the '''southeastern corner of {{ill|Jinraku-ji|ja|秦楽寺|qq=draft|qq=draft}}''') * '''{{ill|Kasayama Kōjinja|ja|笠山荒神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}}''' (Sakurai, '''Kasa''') * '''Hime-Ōji Shrine''' (a subsidiary shrine of Tashinja) * '''{{ill|Shiki Mikenuza Shrine|ja|志貴御県坐神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}}''' (Sakurai, Kanaya) * '''{{ill|Obu Tenjinja|ja|小夫天神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}}''' (Sakurai, Obu) * '''{{ill|Anashizahyozu Shrine|ja|穴師坐兵主神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}}''' (Sakurai, Anashi) * '''{{ill|Asuka Shrine|ja|飛鳥坐神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}}''' ({{ill|Takaichi District, Nara|ja|高市郡|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, '''Asuka Village, Asuka''') * '''Haseyamaguchi Shrine''' (Sakurai, Hase-Tejikarao){{citation needed|date=June 2024}}
Some shrines, such as '''Hibara Shrine, Kasayama Kōjinja, and Obu Tenjinja''', are '''located deep in the mountains'''. Additionally, the name '''Jinraku (秦楽)''', associated with Kasanui Shrine, is also found '''in the plains below the front part of the {{ill|Tsukiyama Kofun|ja|築山古墳|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in {{ill|Yamatotakada, Nara|ja|大和高田市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}''', where it was historically written as '''"神楽" (Jinraku/Kagura)'''. This could suggest some connection{{citation needed|date=June 2024}}.
From '''Tashinja''', looking in the direction of '''Yatsugikamino Mikoto Shrine (矢継ぎ神命神社)''' (dedicated to '''Tenmyō Toyotama no Mikoto'''), one faces the '''Jinraku and Tsukiyama Kofun direction'''. However, due to '''Yatsugi no Mori (矢継ぎの森)''', a sacred grove preserved by locals, '''the view is blocked'''.
It is also speculated that '''in ancient times, the view from Tashinja to Hime-Ōji Shrine may have included the {{ill|Hashihaka Kofun|ja|箸墓|qq=draft|qq=draft}}'''. Originally, '''Hime-Ōji Shrine was located to the north (upper seat) of Tashinja''', but was possibly '''relocated southward (lower seat)'''{{citation needed|date=June 2024}}.
If '''Tashinja is indeed the site of Kasanui-mura''', then these kofun formations might correspond to '''the origins of the {{ill|Daijōsai|ja|大嘗祭|qq=draft|qq=draft}}'s {{ill|Yuki-den|ja|悠紀殿|qq=draft|qq=draft}}''' (which has '''cut-inward 千木 [Chigi] like {{ill|Kōtai Jingu|ja|皇大神宮|1=Kōtai Jingū|2=ja|3=皇大神宮|4=zh|5=皇大神宮|qq=draft|qq=draft}}''') and '''Shuki-den (主基殿)''' (which has '''cut-outward Chigi like {{ill|Toyoukedai Jingu|ja|豊受大神宮|1=Toyouke Daijingu|2=ja|3=豊受大神宮|4=zh|5=豐受大神宮|qq=draft|qq=draft}}'''){{r|Heisei Daijōsai/p182}}{{citation needed|date=June 2024}}.
== Kasanui Island in Osaka == At '''{{ill|Fukae Inari Shrine|ja|深江稲荷神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}}''' ({{ill|Higashinari-ku, Osaka|ja|大阪市 東成区|qq=draft|qq=draft}} '''Fukaeminami'''), there is a tradition that '''Fukae was once the residence of the {{ill|Kasanui clan|ja|笠縫氏|qq=draft|qq=draft}}''', who migrated from '''Kasanui-mura in Yamato'''.
The '''Man'yōshū poet, {{ill|Takechi no Kurohito|ja|高市黒人|qq=draft|qq=draft}}''', wrote: > *"Shihatsu-yama uchi-koe mireba Kasanui no shima kogi-kakuru tana nashi kobune"* > *("Crossing over Mount Shihatsu, I see Kasanui Island, where small boats without roofs disappear.")*
